04415nam a22007695i 9780823241514DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232415147 a10.1515/97808232415142doi  a(DE-B1597)555082  a(OCoLC)785778996  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a809.3041 aSamolsky, Russell, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aApocalyptic Futures :bMarked Bodies and the Violence of the Text in Kafka, Conrad, and Coetzee /cRussell Samolsky. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tfigures -- tacknowledgments -- tintroduction. Writing Violence -- tchapter one. Metaleptic Machines -- tchapter two. Apocalyptic Futures -- tchapter three. The Body in Ruins -- tcoda. The Time of Inscription -- tnotes -- tindex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this book, the author argues that certain modern literary texts have apocalyptic futures. Rather than claim that great writers have clairvoyant powers, he examines the ways in which a text incorporates an apocalyptic event into its future reception. He is thus concerned with the way in which apocalyptic works solicit their future receptions.Apocalyptic Futures also sets out to articulate a new theory and textual practice of the relation between literary reception and embodiment. Deploying the double register of “marks” to show how a text both codes and targets mutilated bodies, the author focuses on how these bodies are incorporated into texts by Kafka, Conrad, Coetzee, and Spiegelman.Situating “In the Penal Colony” in relation to the Holocaust, Heart of Darkness to the Rwandan genocide, and Waiting for the Barbarians to the revelations of torture in apartheid South Africa and contemporary Iraq, the author argues for the ethical and political importance of reading these literary works’ “apocalyptic futures” in our own urgent and perilous situations. The book concludes with a reading of Spiegelman's Maus that offers a messianic counter-time to the law of apocalyptic incorporation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aApocalyptic literature. 0aEthics in literature. 0aFictionxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aMimesis in literature. 0aProphecy in literature. 0aViolence in literature. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPostcolonial Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082323480640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823241514?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823241514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823241514/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK